On Wed, 22 Sep 2004 12:44 am, you wrote:
> Hi Shlomi,
>
>     I know I haven't picked up further on our Ayn Rand thread, but I've run
> across a passage in a book I'd like to quote to you.  This book is "The
> Anatomy of Fascism" by Robert O. Paxton.  I'm almost through it now, and
> consider it a brilliant interpretation of a major aspect of the history of
> the 20th century.
>
>     The author, toward the end, discusses the possibilities of a revival of
> fascism in various environments around the world (including the USA, in an
> interesting way).  I should explain that his definition of fascism is that
> it can arise only where a people become persuaded to "give up free
> institutions" in favor of national unifiicaton.  Hence, by this definition,
> fascism cannot arise in any society that does not have free institutions to
> start with.  Then, he feels obligated to discuss Israel, because Israel
> does have free institutions.  (or purportedly free).  Here's what he says:
>
>     "If religious fascisms are possible, one must address the potential --
> supreme irony -- for fascism in Israel.  Israeli reactions to the first and
> second intifada have been mixed.  Israeli national identity has been
> powerfully associated with an affirmation of the human rights that were
> long denied to Jews in the Diaspora.  This democratic tradition forms a
> barrier against 'giving up free institutions' in the fight against
> Palestinian nationalists.  It has been weakened, however, but two trends --
> the inevitable hardening of attitudes in the face of Palestinian
> intransigence, and a shift in weight within the Israeli population away
> from European Jews, the principal bearers of the democratic tradition, in
> favor of Jews from North Africa and elsewhere in the Near East who are
> indifferent to it.  The suicide bombers of the second intifada after 2001
> radicalized even many Israeli democrats to the right.  By 2002, it was
> possible to hear language within the right wing of the Likud Party and some
> of the small religious parties that comes close to a functional equivalent
> to fasciem.  The chosen people begins to sound like a Master Race that
> claims a unique 'mission in the world,' demands its 'vital space,'
> demonizes an enemy that obstructs the realization of the people's destiny,
> and accepts the necessity of force to obtain these ends."
>
>     Curious to hear how you might react to that passage.
>

I think it very much has a point. I too have felt this, and it worries me a 
bit. One of the things I am most worried about is that Orthodox Jews will 
become a majority, and so use their electoral power to enforce a theocracy. 
This may cause a brain-drain out of Israel, or some secular militias to form, 
or even the Military (which consists mostly of secular or only moderately 
religious people[1]) to go against the government.

This reminds me that I started to write an essay in English about the proper 
solution for the Israeli-Palestinian Problem. I'm attaching the abstract and 
can send you the incomplete draft I have now. It starts with the short-term 
solution and goes on to propose long-term constitutional modifications. 
Everything is based on Liberalist principles.

Once I publish it, I accept quite a lot of resistance from most Israelis, 
because it deviates from everything most of them have been tought.

Regards,

	Shlomi Fish

[1] - Despite being supportive of Israeli occupation of the occupied 
territories, most Orthodox (Haredim) Jews don't serve in the army, and are 
positively incapable of protecting themselves, or Israel at large.

I should note that I did not serve in the Army either, due to my tendencies to 
become depressive or euphoric. I did, however, wanted to serve their 
originally.


